Charlie Monk, an upbeat music industry networker and radio personality known as the Mayor of Music Row, died at home Monday afternoon. He was 84.

Monk, who co-founded the popular Country Radio Seminar more than 50 years ago, earned his nickname by glad-handing and encouraging others for decades in country radio and country music publishing. He hosted the career-launching New Faces show at that radio seminar more than 40 times.

An Alabama native who grew up dirt poor, Monk fought hard to make something of himself − and to be famous, he told The Tennessean three years ago.

Though he felt he never reached that second goal, Monk launched a career in radio and music publishing in which he helped propel many artists to superstardom.

"I’ve helped a lot of people achieve their goals," he said. "I found out I was better at touting other people than I was at touting me.

Among those grateful they met Monk are some of the biggest stars of the genre, including Garth Brooks.

"I love you, pal. I can’t thank you enough for all you’ve done for me," Brooks said in a recent video tribute to Monk for being honored by the Nashville Association of Talent Directors.

"But the truth is, you’ve done it for everybody. You’re one of those guys who knows a lot about everything.... Seriously, man, every time I talk to you, when I leave you, I’m ready to go out and kick the world’s a**. And that is a gift you have. Thank you for sharing it with me."

Video footage released by the City of Memphis on Friday shows how Tyre Nichols, a 29-year-old Black man, suffered a severe beating after a traffic stop by officers of the local Scorpion unit on Jan. 7. Nichols died three days later.

One of the four videos shows Nichols on the ground less than half a mile from where the traffic stop occurred. In the video, officers slap and push Nichols, who screams, “Mom!” Nichols’s mother’s house was 60 yards away.

Five police officers who were involved — Tadarrius Bean, Demetrius Haley, Emmitt Martin III, Desmond Mills Jr. and Justin Smith — have been fired. The officers, who are Black, were charged on Thursday with second-degree murder and kidnapping, among other charges.

Several officials have criticized the excessive use of force, and a separate federal civil rights investigation is also underway. Cerelyn Davis, the Memphis police chief, described the incident in a news conference as “heinous, reckless and inhumane.”

Mayor Jim Strickland of Memphis announced on Friday that the Scorpion unit had been inactive since the incident and that all Memphis Police Department special units were facing independent review.

See a breakdown of the full timeline at the link in our bio.

“This is an emergency within an emergency”.

At the time of writing, more than 7,200 people have died and 32,000 are injured across Türkiye and Syria, following yesterday’s devastating earthquake that struck the heart of the world’s largest refugee population. There are warnings that the number of deaths could exceed 20,000.	

Freezing temperatures and aftershocks are hampering rescue efforts and countless numbers of people are now homeless, adding to the millions already displaced due to the ongoing Syrian conflict. 

This is critical. Time is of the essence to find remaining survivors and agencies urgently needing financial support. People are in desperate need of shelter, food and hygiene items. 

The Looking Out Foundation will match all donations up to $100,000 over the next week and this will be distributed to @akutdernegi and @the_whitehelmets. 

AKUT is a Turkish Search & Rescue organization that specializes in disaster relief. They have 28 teams and 646 volunteers currently working day and night in the rescue effort.

The White Helmets (Syria Civil Defence) are a group of around 3000 volunteers on the ground in north west Syria leading the search and rescue operation.

Donations can be made via our Instagram profile or on our website (link in bio)

We are thrilled to welcome @shellyfairchild to the KRS family and to share the video for Shelly + @shamir326’s cover of Loretta Lynn’s “Fist City”!

Having had her share of trials and tribulations navigating the overwhelmingly straight nature of record label titans, Shelly Fairchild carved out a space for herself as a highly respected and established queer country artist whether or not the powers that be approved. Nashville, Tennessee based and Jackson, Mississippi born, Fairchild has toured with an array of artists spanning from Tanya Tucker to Martina McBride, and her songs have been featured on various TV programs such as Grey’s Anatomy, Selling Sunset, and Riverdale. She is a regular guest on the Grand Ole Opry, hosts a monthly LGBTQ+ night at famed Nashville institution Lipstick Lounge, and was named one of Rolling Stone Country’s “Top 10 Artists You Need To Know.” Her work is bluesy, potent, and distinctive—informed and driven by her identity, relationships, and struggles both personal and professional. New to the Kill Rock Stars family, she is currently writing and recording her next fearlessly honest and self-expressive full-length album, unimpeded by a bunch of heterosexual men in suits.

Stream the tribute to country music icon, Loretta Lynn, on the streaming platform of your choice + watch the full video directed by Ford Fairchild- shot at Loretta Lynn Ranch, Hurricane Mills, TN - using the links in our bio

OUT NOW!!! The official music video for @shellyfairchild + @shamir326’s cover of Loretta Lynn’s “Fist City”.

Known for his evocative lyrics and androgynous vocals, Shamir’s art is a synthesis of the full spectrum of human emotion; sensual, furious, yearning, clever, joyful. The expressive freedom in his work, although tethered through style to greats (like Miss Nina Simone, Prince, and Taylor Swift), is based in a hyper specific, fully autonomous examination of personhood. After joining Kill Rock Stars, Shamir remastered and re-released his 2017 self-produced album, Hope, (alongside a wildly popular vinyl pressing) where he connected with Shelly Fairchild after Loretta Lynn’s passing.

“The music of Loretta Lynn has always been a source of comfort. My love of country first began when I got my first radio when I was 9 years old. Every Sunday morning my local country station would play classic country and oldies, of course Loretta’s music was frequently played. Then someone down the line Coal Miner’s Daughter became a comfort movie of mine. I’ve seen it at least a dozen times. Slim saw my tweet about the movie being a comfort film of mine and told me Shelly started the Fist City cover. I was more than happy to be a part of it. The cherry on top of it all was being able to shoot in Hurricane Mills, it was incredible to see all her awards and collectibles.”

-Shamir

Shot at Loretta Lynn Ranch, Hurricane Mills, TN and 🎥 by Ford Fairchild.

social_posts.post_text: Join Country Proud at the @OfficialCMHoF on Saturday, April 8, for a special concert and conversation, hosted by the Museum's Angela Stefano Zimmer. Country Proud is @rnbw.collective country music–focused showcase series, a collective of Nashville’s LGBTQ+ performers, songwriters, and musicians founded in 2016 to create an inclusive space for all music lovers. Co-founders Emily and Jamie Dryburgh (@theEmilyDryburgh, @JamieDryburgh) and artists @ShellyFairchild, @OfficialAngieK, @SoniaLeigh, and @AdamMac will discuss the organization’s history, goals, and impact as well as their experiences as queer artists in country music. Don’t miss RNBW and the Museum’s first collaboration—get tickets today! Visit CountryMusicHallofFame.org to learn more. @officialcmhof 💛

1. Make homemade biscuits from scratch and feed all of the family that came to town to hear me sing on the @opry 
2. Sit around the kitchen table singjng with one’s gorgeous niece and watch my daddy play his daddy’s guitar 
3. Thumb thru newest photoshoot that @fordfairchild so masterfully shot out at the QUEEN @lorettalynnofficial ‘s ranch. @lorettalynnranchofficial  4 life! 🤘🏼❤️
4. Remember that I found this cool lil @opry @barbie at a vintage shop and laugh at the fact that it was only $25 and I’m so happy it’s mine! (Tho I MIGHT color her hair brown sometime soon)
5. Have a love fest over how my precious friend @shamir326 loves @lorettalynnofficial so much and said yes to singing FIST CITY with me. 
6. And then this….. my heart is so happy to be showing up tonight to sing on one of the most important stages that has ever existed. I can’t believe I get to do it… to be there… in the circle…. Along with my lovely guitar man @garrettstoner and my sweetest and long time friend @cdjinthehouse singing with her perfect voice and her gentle spirit. 

Life can sure put some weird food on your plate… but WOW how amazing it feels when you just toss that weird food plate out the window…. And start again.
